Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me compile all findings into a thorough answer.

---

Here is a detailed catalogue of TigerBeetle's idiomatic patterns for validating valid subsets of parameter combinations, drawn from across the codebase. They use four distinct patterns, and frequently layer them.

---

## Pattern 1: `switch` on the Primary Discriminant, `assert`/Inline-checks on Each Arm

This is the dominant pattern. You switch on the "controlling" parameter and then assert or validate the secondary one within each arm.

### Example A — `invalid_header()` in [`message_header.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/message_header.zig#L632)

Each `Command` header type has an `invalid_header()` method that returns a `?[]const u8`. It switches on `operation` (the second parameter) and enforces which other fields are legal within each arm:

```zig
fn invalid_header(self: *const @This()) ?[]const u8 {
    assert(self.command == .request);       // outer discriminant already known
    ...
    switch (self.operation) {
        .reserved => return "operation == .reserved",
        .root     => return "operation == .root",
        .register => {
            // Only certain fields are allowed when operation == .register
            if (self.replica != 0) return "register: replica != 0";
            if (self.client  == 0) return "register: client == 0";
            if (self.session != 0) return "register: session != 0";
            if (self.request != 0) return "register: request != 0";
        },
        .pulse => {
            // Completely different constraints for .pulse
            if (self.client != 0) return "pulse: client != 0";
            if (self.session != 0) return "pulse: session != 0";
        },
        .upgrade => {
            if (self.client != 0) return "upgrade: client != 0";
            if (self.size != @sizeOf(Header) + @sizeOf(vsr.UpgradeRequest)) {
                return "upgrade: size != ...";
            }
        },
        else => {
            // For remaining operations, different rules apply
            if (self.client == 0) return "client == 0";
            if (self.session == 0) return "session == 0";
        },
    }
    ...
    return null;
}
```

The key insight: `command` is already encoded in the struct's concrete type (`Header.Request`), so `assert(self.command == .request)` fires first — then `operation` is the combinatorial second axis. The pattern returns a `?[]const u8` (null = valid) rather than crashing, so callers can choose to log, drop, or crash.

### Example B — `Prepare.invalid_header()`: `operation` determines which *other* fields are allowed

```zig
switch (self.operation) {
    .reserved => {
        if (self.view != 0)             return "reserved: view != 0";
        if (self.release.value != 0)    return "release != 0";
        if (self.client != 0)           return "reserved: client != 0";
        if (self.timestamp != 0)        return "reserved: timestamp != 0";
    },
    .root => {
        if (self.view != 0)             return "root: view != 0";
        if (self.op != 0)               return "root: op != 0";
        if (self.client != 0)           return "root: client != 0";
    },
    else => {
        if (self.release.value == 0)    return "release == 0";
        // .pulse/.upgrade have client == 0; everything else requires client != 0
        if (self.operation == .pulse or self.operation == .upgrade) {
            if (self.client != 0) return "client != 0";
        } else {
            if (self.client == 0) return "client == 0";
        }
        // .register/.pulse/.upgrade require request == 0; others require request != 0
        if (self.operation == .register or
            self.operation == .pulse    or
            self.operation == .upgrade)
        {
            if (self.request != 0) return "request != 0";
        } else {
            if (self.request == 0) return "request == 0";
        }
    },
}
```

---

## Pattern 2: `switch` with `else => unreachable` to Partition the Legal Subset

When some combinations are structurally impossible, TigerBeetle marks them `unreachable` directly:

### Example A — `scope_open` in [`state_machine.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/state_machine.zig#L2876)

Not every `Operation` can `scope_open`. Only create-operations can. Others are `unreachable`:

```zig
fn scope_open(self: *StateMachine, operation: Operation) void {
    switch (operation) {
        .create_accounts,
        .deprecated_create_accounts_sparse,
        .deprecated_create_accounts_unbatched,
        => {
            self.forest.grooves.accounts.scope_open();
        },
        .create_transfers,
        .deprecated_create_transfers_sparse,
        .deprecated_create_transfers_unbatched,
        => {
            self.forest.grooves.accounts.scope_open();
            self.forest.grooves.transfers.scope_open();
            self.forest.grooves.transfers_pending.scope_open();
            self.forest.grooves.account_events.scope_open();
        },
        else => unreachable,  // ← only create-ops may ever call this
    }
}
```

### Example B — `TrailerNode.metadata()` in [`schema.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/lsm/schema.zig#L432)

A `TrailerNode` can only be `.free_set` or `.client_sessions`. The `block_type` is one axis; the allowed body size formula is the other:

```zig
switch (header.block_type) {
    .free_set => {
        assert((header.size - @sizeOf(vsr.Header)) % @sizeOf(u64) == 0);
    },
    .client_sessions => {
        assert((header.size - @sizeOf(vsr.Header)) %
            (@sizeOf(vsr.Header) + @sizeOf(u64)) == 0);
    },
    else => unreachable,   // ← no other block_type is a valid TrailerNode
}
```

### Example C — `execute` / `execute_multi_batch` in [`state_machine.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/state_machine.zig#L2596)

Combinations between `operation` and calling path are enforced with `comptime unreachable`:

```zig
fn execute(self: *StateMachine, comptime operation: Operation, ...) usize {
    comptime assert(!operation.is_multi_batch());   // ← compile-time guard first

    switch (operation) {
        .deprecated_create_accounts_unbatched,
        .deprecated_create_transfers_unbatched,
        => return self.execute_create(...),
        .deprecated_lookup_accounts_unbatched   => return self.execute_lookup_accounts(...),
        .deprecated_lookup_transfers_unbatched  => return self.execute_lookup_transfers(...),
        else => comptime unreachable,  // ← no other op should reach this path
    }
}
```

---

## Pattern 3: Inline Boolean Expression (for Mutually Exclusive Flag Combinations)

When parameters are flag bits rather than enum tags, TigerBeetle checks forbidden co-occurrences with boolean expressions and returns an error code immediately:

### Example — `post_or_void_pending_transfer` in [`state_machine.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/state_machine.zig#L3960)

```zig
fn post_or_void_pending_transfer(
    self: *StateMachine,
    timestamp_event: u64,
    t: *const Transfer,
) CreateTransferStatusUnion {
    assert(t.flags.post_pending_transfer or t.flags.void_pending_transfer);

    // Two flags are mutually exclusive:
    if (t.flags.post_pending_transfer and t.flags.void_pending_transfer) {
        return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
    }
    // These flags cannot co-exist with post/void:
    if (t.flags.pending)          return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
    if (t.flags.balancing_debit)  return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
    if (t.flags.balancing_credit) return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
    if (t.flags.closing_debit)    return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
    if (t.flags.closing_credit)   return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;

    // Now we know: exactly one of post/void is set, and none of the above are set.
    ...
}
```

Also in `create_account`:
```zig
if (a.flags.debits_must_not_exceed_credits and a.flags.credits_must_not_exceed_debits) {
    return .flags_are_mutually_exclusive;
}
```

---

## Pattern 4: Comptime-Parameterized Type — Only Some Operations Are Structurally Valid

For compile-time known operations, TigerBeetle uses `comptime` to produce the right type from the combination, preventing invalid combos at compile time entirely.

### Example — `transient_error` in [`state_machine.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/state_machine.zig#L3131)

The `result_status` parameter's *type* changes based on `operation`. Non-create operations hit `else => unreachable` at comptime:

```zig
fn transient_error(
    self: *StateMachine,
    comptime operation: Operation,
    id: u128,
    result_status: switch (operation) {   // ← type of this param depends on `operation`
        .create_accounts,
        .deprecated_create_accounts_sparse,
        .deprecated_create_accounts_unbatched,
        => CreateAccountStatus,

        .create_transfers,
        .deprecated_create_transfers_sparse,
        .deprecated_create_transfers_unbatched,
        => CreateTransferStatus,

        else => unreachable,   // ← compile error if called with any other operation
    },
) void { ... }
```

### Example — `CreateTransferStatusUnion` / `CreateAccountStatusUnion`

A tagged union produced via comptime mapping — only `.created` and `.exists` carry a `u64` timestamp payload; all other error tags carry `void`:

```zig
const CreateTransferStatusUnion = stdx.EnumUnionType(
    CreateTransferStatus,
    struct {
        fn Type(comptime result: CreateTransferStatus) type {
            return switch (result) {
                .created, .exists => u64,  // ← valid combination: payload present
                else              => void, // ← all error cases: no payload
            };
        }
    }.Type,
);
```

---

## Pattern 5: `switch` on State with Per-State Assertions (`assert` + `maybe`)

For pairs of (state, invariant), TigerBeetle uses a switch where each branch asserts what must hold for the other parameters. From [`state_machine.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/state_machine.zig#L206):

```zig
switch (self.transfer_pending_status) {
    .none, .pending => assert(self.transfer_pending_id == 0),
    .posted, .voided, .expired => assert(self.transfer_pending_id != 0),
}
```

And from [`client_replies.zig`](https://github.com/tigerbeetle/tigerbeetle/blob/main/src/vsr/client_replies.zig#L345):

```zig
switch (trigger) {
    .commit => {
        assert(client_replies.checkpoint_callback == null);
        maybe(client_replies.faulty.is_set(slot.index)); // may or may not be set
    },
    .repair => {
        maybe(client_replies.checkpoint_callback == null);
        assert(client_replies.faulty.is_set(slot.index)); // MUST be set for repair
    },
}
```

---

## Summary of Patterns

| Pattern | When used | TigerBeetle idiom |
|---|---|---|
| `switch` + per-arm field checks | (enum, other fields) combos | `fn invalid_header()` returning `?[]const u8` |
| `switch` + `else => unreachable` | Strict subset of enum values | `scope_open`, `execute`, `TrailerNode.metadata` |
| Sequential boolean guards | Flag-bit co-exclusion | `flags_are_mutually_exclusive` return |
| `comptime switch` on type | Compile-time invalid combos | `transient_error`, comptime union type |
| `switch` + `assert`/`maybe` per arm | State-machine invariants | `transfer_pending_status`, `WriteTrigger` |

### Applied to Your Zig Function

For a `(base: u8, diacritic: Diacritic) → result` validator, the TigerBeetle pattern would be:

```zig
fn apply_diacritic(base: u8, diacritic: Diacritic) !u21 {
    switch (diacritic) {
        .acute => switch (base) {
            'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u', 'A', 'E', 'I', 'O', 'U' => {
                // valid — produce codepoint
            },
            else => return error.InvalidCombination,
        },
        .cedilla => switch (base) {
            'c', 'C', 's', 'S' => {
                // valid
            },
            else => return error.InvalidCombination,
        },
        // ... other diacritics
    }
}
```

Or, for a pure assertion (where the caller guarantees validity), TigerBeetle would use `assert` at the top with `unreachable` in the catch-all:

```zig
fn apply_diacritic(base: u8, diacritic: Diacritic) u21 {
    switch (diacritic) {
        .acute => assert(std.mem.indexOfScalar(u8, "aeiouAEIOU", base) != null),
        .cedilla => assert(std.mem.indexOfScalar(u8, "cCsS", base) != null),
    }
    // ...
}
```

The library-facing boundary prefers the `?[]const u8` / error union return (like `invalid_header`); the internal fast path prefers bare `assert` + `unreachable`.
